Here are two practical, production-ready examples of multi-stage builds across two completely different tech stacks.  
Each example demonstrates how to compile the application in a heavy, tool-filled builder stage, and then copy only the essential compiled output into a tiny runtime stage.  
Example 1: Node.js / React (Compiled into Nginx Static Server)
Stage 1 Base Image (node:20-alpine): Includes Node.js, npm, and build tools.  
Stage 2 Base Image (nginx:alpine): Extremely lightweight web server (~20–30 MB) with no Node.js runtime.

Dockerfile
# ==========================================
# STAGE 1: Build Stage (Heavy Node Environment)
# ==========================================
FROM node:20-alpine AS builder

WORKDIR /app

# Copy package files and install ALL dependencies
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install

# Copy source code and build the static production bundle
COPY . .
RUN npm run build

# ==========================================
# STAGE 2: Runtime Stage (Lightweight Nginx Server)
# ==========================================
FROM nginx:alpine AS runner

# Copy ONLY the static dist/build files from Stage 1 into Nginx's web root
COPY --from=builder /app/dist /usr/share/nginx/html

# Expose standard web traffic port
EXPOSE 80

CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]

Result: Drops image size from ~1 GB (Node + node_modules + source code) down to ~30 MB (pure compiled HTML/JS served by Nginx)!
Example 2: Go / Golang (Compiled into a Zero-Byte scratch Image)Stage 1 Base Image (golang:1.22): Heavy Go SDK, compilers, and system utilities.Stage 2 Base Image (scratch): Docker’s absolute minimalist base image (literally 0 MB in size).Dockerfile# ==========================================
# STAGE 1: Build Stage (Full Go SDK & Compiler)
# ==========================================
FROM golang:1.22 AS builder

WORKDIR /src

# Download dependencies separately to leverage layer caching
COPY go.mod go.sum ./
RUN go mod download

# Copy source code and compile a standalone, statically-linked binary
COPY . .
RUN CGO_ENABLED=0 GOOS=linux go build -o /app/server .


# ==========================================
# STAGE 2: Runtime Stage (Absolute Zero OS Overhead)
# ==========================================
FROM scratch AS runner

# Copy ONLY the compiled binary file from Stage 1
COPY --from=builder /app/server /server

# Set entrypoint to run the binary directly
ENTRYPOINT ["/server"]

Result: Leaves the Go compiler, SDK, and source code completely behind in Stage 1.
The resulting production image is literally just the binary file itself (~10–15 MB total).